Part I - Used Car Data Exploration and Visualizations¶

by Betabasi Daniel¶

Introduction¶

Used Car Data¶

This dataset includes information (e.g. Sales_ID, name, year, selling_price, km_driven, Region, State or Province, City, fuel, seller_type, transmission, owner, mileage, engine, max_power, torque, seats, sold) of different types of used cars across the market gathered by a consulting firm based on various market surveys for an automobile company XYZ from India which aspires to enter the Indian used car market.

The Indian used car market, according to Mordor Intelligence during the forecast period (2022-2027) is projected to grow by 15.1% Compound Annual Growth Rate (CAGR) to reach 74.70 Billion Dollars in 2027 from an estimated value of 32.14 Billion Dollars in 2021. The COVID-19 epidemic hardly affected the sector. The market for used cars is expected to expand significantly as more individuals choose independent mobility and as additional financing alternatives become available.

Questions for the Data Analysis¶

  1. Which variables are significant in predicting the price of a used car?

  2. How well does those variables describe the price of a car?

  3. Which brands are selling the most?

  4. Are there specific locations selling more?

  5. Which factors are more important in deciding cars' selling price?

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset has 7906 entries of used cars with 18 features (which are Sales_ID, name, year, selling_price, km_driven, Region, State or Province, City, fuel, seller_type, transmission, owner, mileage, engine, max_power, torque, seats and sold). The data types of the variables consist of 2 floats, 6 integers, and 10 strings.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

My main features of interest is to determine the variables that are significant in predicting the price of a used car and to investigate the sales of used cars made over the years.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The features in the dataset that will help support my investigation into my features of interest are the different car variables and the different locations where the sales of used cars were recorded.

Data Cleaning¶

df_clean = df.copy()
In [10]:
# define a function to clean the torque column
def parser(item):
    item = item.replace(" ", "")
    item = item.replace(",", "")
    item = item.replace("at","@")
    item = item.replace("n", "")
    item = item.replace("NM", "")
    item = item.replace("KGM", "")
    item = item.replace("Nm(38.7kgm)", "")
    item = item.replace("Nm/2000", "")
    item = item.replace("(11.2)", "")
    item = item.replace("/1900", "")
    item = item.rstrip("rpm")
    item = item.rstrip("(kgm@rpm)")
    items = item.split("@")
    items[0] = items[0].rstrip("Nm")
    items[0] = items[0].rstrip("kgm")
    return "=".join(items[:2])
In [11]:
# split the torque into two lists of torque and rotational speed
new_torque = list(map(parser, df['torque']))

torque = list(map(lambda i: i.split("=")[0], new_torque))
rotational_speed = list(map(lambda i: i.split("=")[-1], new_torque))
In [12]:
# define a function to extract the maximum rotational speed
def parse(item):
    item = item.replace("1500~", "")
    item = item.replace("RPM", "")
    items = item.split("-")
    items = max(items)
    return items
In [13]:
# create new torque and max_RPM columns from the old torque
max_rotation = list(map(parse, rotational_speed))

df_clean["torque"] = torque
df_clean["max_RPM"] = max_rotation

Observation¶

Among the distributions of the different attributes, the selling price and maximum power is happen to be right skewed and caught my interest. I will perform a scale transformation on the two variables, selling price and maximum power.

What is the distribution of the selling prices of used cars?¶

In [25]:
# Resize the chart, and have two plots side-by-side
# set a larger figure size for subplots
plt.figure(figsize = [16, 5]) 

# histogram on left, 1 row, 2 cols, subplot 1
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)# histogram on left, 1 row, 2 cols, subplot 1
log_binsize = 0.075
bins = 10 ** np.arange(4.5, np.log10(df_clean['selling_price'].max())+log_binsize, log_binsize)

plt.hist(data = df_clean, x = 'selling_price', bins = bins)
plt.title('Histogram Showing the Normal Distribution of the Selling Prices')
plt.ylabel('Frequency Count')
plt.xlabel('Price ($)');

# histogram on left, 1 row, 2 cols, subplot 2
plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)

# there's a long tail in the distribution, so let's put it on a log scale instead
log_binsize = 0.075
bins = 10 ** np.arange(4.5, np.log10(df_clean['selling_price'].max())+log_binsize, log_binsize)

plt.hist(data = df_clean, x = 'selling_price', bins = bins)
plt.title('Histogram Showing the Log Transformation for the Selling Prices')
plt.xscale('log')
plt.xticks([2e4, 4e4, 8e4, 16e4, 4e5, 1e6, 2e6, 5e6, 1e7], ['20k', '40k', '90k', '180k', '400k', '1M', '2M', '5M', '10M'])
plt.ylabel('Frequency Count')
plt.xlabel('Price ($)');

Observation¶

Our initial distribution of selling prices was unimodal so I did a log transformation on it to normalize it.

Conclusions¶

My features of interest are the selling prices of cars and the variables that are significant in predicting the prices of cars are maximum power, torque and engine. There were little unusual points in some of the variables but I did a log transformation on my most significant features of interest, selling price and the maximum power to normalise them since I discovered in my exploration that they were both right skewed.

From my exploration, the greater the maximum power, torque and engine of the cars, the higher their selling prices. Cars that sells more run on either diesel or petrol and they are mostly of the manual transmission type having first owner as their owner type and being sold by individuals. The locations where these sales were made which includes the regions, states and cities helps to strengthen their relationship between the car features and the total number of sales made.
